(PLAYING UPBEAT TUNE)

52
00:06:53,455 --> 00:06:54,745
(MUSIC ENDS)

53
00:07:01,713 --> 00:07:03,053
(CHUCKLING)

54
00:07:05,508 --> 00:07:07,048
(PLAYING OFF-KEY)

55
00:07:07,093 --> 00:07:09,183
All right, all right, all right, all right.

56
00:07:10,722 --> 00:07:11,972
Into bed.

57
00:07:12,390 --> 00:07:14,060
Into bed. Thank you for the music.

58
00:07:14,225 --> 00:07:15,385
-Come on.
-Ouch.

59
00:07:15,518 --> 00:07:17,228
Get in there. Come on.

60
00:07:18,980 --> 00:07:20,070
Give me a kiss.

61
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:24,610
I love you, Margaret.

62
00:07:25,528 --> 00:07:26,528
I love you, too.

63
00:07:27,405 --> 00:07:28,735
Sleep well.

64
00:07:30,658 --> 00:07:32,238
(BLOWING)
I'll take this.

65
00:07:34,996 --> 00:07:37,416
I don't want to
hear any more noise.

66
00:07:45,423 --> 00:07:46,723
(CHILDREN GIGGLING)

67
00:07:48,510 --> 00:07:51,050
(SIGHS) Three weeks and two days.

68
00:07:51,179 --> 00:07:53,309
It is the custom.

69
00:07:53,431 --> 00:07:55,641
I wonder what you will do without me.

70
00:07:56,518 --> 00:07:58,478
I won't stay idle.

71
00:08:00,063 --> 00:08:02,233
Darling, it's good money.

72
00:08:04,317 --> 00:08:07,487
If only I didn't have
to share your cooking with other people.

73
00:08:09,114 --> 00:08:11,074
You don't.

74
00:08:15,245 --> 00:08:16,245
(GRUNTS)

75
00:08:16,329 --> 00:08:18,999
Be good for your mother. Okay, Alonzo?

76
00:08:20,542 --> 00:08:22,962
Can I get a kiss, please? Thank you.

77
00:08:23,503 --> 00:08:24,503
Travel safely.

78
00:08:24,629 --> 00:08:26,169
Stay safely.

79
00:08:29,467 --> 00:08:30,637
Ready?

80
00:08:30,719 --> 00:08:32,049
(DRIVER URGING HORSES)

81
00:08:39,227 --> 00:08:39,977
(CHILDREN LAUGHING)

82
00:08:40,061 --> 00:08:40,731
(BELLS TOLLING)

83
00:08:46,276 --> 00:08:47,986
MR. MOON: Devil
call his name, there he is now.

84
00:08:48,111 --> 00:08:49,401
Mr. Northup!

85
00:08:49,487 --> 00:08:52,277
I have two gentlemen
whose acquaintance you should make.

86
00:08:52,407 --> 00:08:54,407
Misters Brown
and Hamilton.

87
00:08:54,576 --> 00:08:55,616
Sir.

88
00:08:55,994 --> 00:08:57,624
Mr. Northup, these two gentlemen...

89
00:08:57,996 --> 00:09:00,326
were inquiring about
distinguished individuals...

90
00:09:00,457 --> 00:09:02,207
and I was just this very moment...

91
00:09:02,375 --> 00:09:05,455
saying Solomon Northup
is an expert player on the violin.

92
00:09:05,587 --> 00:09:06,957
He was indeed.

93
00:09:07,047 --> 00:09:08,167
Mr. Moon is being overly gracious.

94
00:09:08,298 --> 00:09:09,588
Well, taking into consideration

95
00:09:09,716 --> 00:09:11,216
his graciousness and your modesty...

96
00:09:11,384 --> 00:09:14,394
may we trouble you
for a moment of your time to converse, sir?

97
00:09:14,471 --> 00:09:15,721
Of course.

98
00:09:16,222 --> 00:09:17,352
Good day.

99
00:09:17,599 --> 00:09:19,059
SOLOMON: <i>A circus?</i>

100
00:09:19,184 --> 00:09:20,194
That is our usual employee.

101
00:09:20,310 --> 00:09:21,730
The company currently
in the city of Washington.

102
00:09:22,062 --> 00:09:23,612
Circus is too constricting a word...

103
00:09:23,980 --> 00:09:26,400
to describe the talented and merry
band with which we travel.

104
00:09:26,483 --> 00:09:29,443
It is a spectacle
unlike most have ever witnessed.

105
00:09:29,569 --> 00:09:31,279
Creatures from the darkest Africa

106
00:09:31,404 --> 00:09:33,074
as yet unseen by civilized man.

107
00:09:33,365 --> 00:09:34,565
Acrobats from the Orient...

108
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:37,699
who contort themselves
in the most confounding manners.

109
00:09:37,744 --> 00:09:39,754
(LAUGHS) And I myself
in aide of Mr. Brown...

110
00:09:40,080 --> 00:09:41,620
an internationally renowned practitioner

111
00:09:41,748 --> 00:09:43,458
in the art of prestidigitation.

112
00:09:43,583 --> 00:09:45,043
We are on our way thither to rejoin

113
00:09:45,210 --> 00:09:46,460
the company having left for a short time...

114
00:09:46,586 --> 00:09:48,706
to make a small profit from
our own exhibitions.

115
00:09:49,047 --> 00:09:50,587
The reason for our inquiry with Mr. Moon--

116
00:09:50,715 --> 00:09:52,505
Yes. We had just a devil of a time

117
00:09:52,592 --> 00:09:54,392
in procuring music for our entertainments.

118
00:09:54,552 --> 00:09:56,552
Men of true talents are
seemingly in short supply.

119
00:09:56,721 --> 00:09:57,721
Thank you, sir.

120
00:09:58,056 --> 00:10:00,976
If we could persuade you
to accompany us as far as Washington--

121
00:10:01,059 --> 00:10:03,439
We could give you one dollar
for each day's services...

122
00:10:03,561 --> 00:10:06,021
and three dollars for every night
played at our performances.

123
00:10:06,147 --> 00:10:07,977
In addition, we would
provide sufficient pay...

124
00:10:08,066 --> 00:10:11,146
for your return here to Saratoga,
two weeks from today.

125
00:10:16,324 --> 00:10:18,494
Welcome to Washington,
Solomon.

126
00:10:19,244 --> 00:10:21,084
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

127
00:10:24,499 --> 00:10:26,079
(ALL LAUGHING)

128
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:28,337
Hamilton, you know too much.

129
00:10:28,461 --> 00:10:30,051
Some say not enough.

130
00:10:30,422 --> 00:10:33,972
Solomon, 43 dollars. All to you.

131
00:10:35,051 --> 00:10:37,011
That is far more
than my wages amount to.

132
00:10:37,137 --> 00:10:38,597
BROWN: It's been a most
profitable week, sir.

133
00:10:38,972 --> 00:10:40,142
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

134
00:10:40,265 --> 00:10:41,465
Cheers.

135
00:10:46,146 --> 00:10:47,556
Another.

136
00:10:49,232 --> 00:10:54,242
Gentlemen, your generosity
is extraordinary.

137
00:10:54,362 --> 00:10:56,412
And your talents are undeniable.

138
00:10:56,489 --> 00:10:57,529
Mmm. To Solomon.

139
00:10:57,657 --> 00:10:58,987
Cheers.

140
00:10:59,075 --> 00:11:00,235
Cheers.

141
00:11:11,004 --> 00:11:12,214
(CHAINS RATTLING)

142
00:11:21,598 --> 00:11:23,478
(RATTLING CONTINUES)

143
00:11:40,700 --> 00:11:41,530
Ugh!

144
00:11:41,618 --> 00:11:42,488
(GROANING)

145
00:11:44,037 --> 00:11:45,537
It's all right, Solomon.

146
00:11:45,663 --> 00:11:47,003
There's no shame in it.

147
00:11:47,082 --> 00:11:48,382
No shame at all.

148
00:11:58,551 --> 00:12:00,051
(GRUNTING)

149
00:12:10,355 --> 00:12:11,225
(WHISPERS) Hamilton, we must hurry.

150
00:12:11,314 --> 00:12:12,194
(SOLOMON GROANING)

151
00:12:13,233 --> 00:12:14,403
One too many libation.

152
00:12:14,442 --> 00:12:15,072
(SOLOMON COUGHS)

153
00:12:15,193 --> 00:12:15,613
We're halfway there.

154
00:12:15,735 --> 00:12:17,235
(CHAINS RATTLING LOUDLY)

155
00:12:20,407 --> 00:12:21,697
(GRUNTING)

156
00:12:29,541 --> 00:12:30,711
(PANTING)

157
00:12:32,585 --> 00:12:34,045
SOLOMON: <i>So sorry--</i>

158
00:12:34,087 --> 00:12:35,167
(SHUSHING)

159
00:12:35,213 --> 00:12:37,053
We won't hear it. We won't.

160
00:12:37,215 --> 00:12:39,215
Let him sleep, Hamilton.

161
00:12:39,259 --> 00:12:41,719
Mmm. A good night's rest.

162
00:12:42,345 --> 00:12:44,055
And tomorrow...

163
00:12:45,181 --> 00:12:47,391
tomorrow you will feel
as well and refreshed

164
00:12:47,475 --> 00:12:49,725
as if the earth were new again.

165
00:12:50,061 --> 00:12:52,611
(SCOFFS) Hamilton,
there's nothing more we can do for him.

166
00:12:54,482 --> 00:12:55,732
Such is the pity.

167
00:12:55,984 --> 00:12:57,244
(BLOWING)

168
00:12:59,279 --> 00:13:00,409
(GASPING)

169
00:13:03,158 --> 00:13:04,408
(DOOR OPENS)

170
00:13:05,410 --> 00:13:08,290
Well, boy, how do you feel now?

171
00:13:10,582 --> 00:13:14,462
My name-- My name is Solomon Northup.

172
00:13:14,586 --> 00:13:18,006
I'm a free man.
A resident of Saratoga, New York.

173
00:13:18,131 --> 00:13:20,631
The residence of
my wife and children who are equally free.

174
00:13:20,967 --> 00:13:22,677
And you have no
right whatsoever to detain me.

175
00:13:23,011 --> 00:13:24,351
You're not any free man.

176
00:13:24,471 --> 00:13:25,681
And I promise you...

177
00:13:26,014 --> 00:13:28,144
I promise you upon my liberation

178
00:13:28,224 --> 00:13:30,394
I will have satisfaction for this wrong.

179
00:13:32,103 --> 00:13:33,483
Resolve this.

180
00:13:34,022 --> 00:13:35,482
Produce your papers.

181
00:13:43,406 --> 00:13:45,236
You're no free man.

182
00:13:45,742 --> 00:13:47,662
And you ain't from Saratoga.

183
00:13:48,286 --> 00:13:50,246
You're from Georgia.

184
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:55,383
You ain't a free man.

185
00:13:57,212 --> 00:14:01,342
You're nothing but a Georgia runaway.

186
00:14:03,385 --> 00:14:08,055
You're just a runaway nigger...

187
00:14:08,556 --> 00:14:10,426
from Georgia.

188
00:14:26,700 --> 00:14:27,410
(GRUNTS)

189
00:14:27,534 --> 00:14:28,284
(GROANS)

190
00:14:29,035 --> 00:14:30,245
(PANTING)

191
00:14:33,665 --> 00:14:35,035
(GROANING)

192
00:14:41,631 --> 00:14:43,381
You're a slave!

193
00:14:43,967 --> 00:14:46,467
You're a Georgia slave!

194
00:14:46,511 --> 00:14:48,051
(SCREAMING)

195
00:14:50,098 --> 00:14:51,468
(PANTING)

196
00:15:03,361 --> 00:15:05,071
Are you a slave?

197
00:15:06,281 --> 00:15:07,451
No.

198
00:15:10,702 --> 00:15:12,082
(GROANING)

199
00:15:22,005 --> 00:15:23,205
(GRUNTING)

200
00:15:23,256 --> 00:15:25,466
(SOBBING IN PAIN)

201
00:15:33,058 --> 00:15:35,228
(GASPING)

202
00:15:51,284 --> 00:15:51,744
(DOOR CLOSES)

203
00:15:52,035 --> 00:15:52,445
(LOCK CLICKS)

204
00:15:53,411 --> 00:15:55,081
(SOLOMON GROANING)

205
00:15:57,082 --> 00:15:59,002
(CHAINS RATTLING)

206
00:16:05,465 --> 00:16:07,045
SOLOMON: (SOBBING) Help.

207
00:16:08,259 --> 00:16:10,049
Help me.

208
00:16:11,388 --> 00:16:13,178
Help me!

209
00:16:13,723 --> 00:16:16,233
Somebody help me!

210
00:16:16,976 --> 00:16:19,056
Help!

211
00:16:20,730 --> 00:16:22,320
Help!

212
00:16:27,320 --> 00:16:28,570
(DOOR OPENS)

213
00:16:34,077 --> 00:16:36,747
That old thing of yours
is just rags and tatters.

214
00:16:37,080 --> 00:16:39,420
You need something
proper to wear.

215
00:16:42,460 --> 00:16:44,710
Go on, put it on.

216
00:17:04,232 --> 00:17:05,482
There.

217
00:17:08,987 --> 00:17:10,317
That's fine.

218
00:17:10,655 --> 00:17:12,615
That's fine.

219
00:17:14,993 --> 00:17:16,083
Got no gratitude?

220
00:17:21,416 --> 00:17:22,416
No. That's from my wife.

221
00:17:22,542 --> 00:17:24,212
Rags and tatters.

222
00:17:24,377 --> 00:17:26,707
Rags and tatters.

223
00:17:28,965 --> 00:17:30,215
(DOOR CLOSES)

224
00:17:36,723 --> 00:17:38,523
Go on, wash up.

225
00:17:41,436 --> 00:17:43,306
The boy, too.
Get him clean.

226
00:17:46,066 --> 00:17:47,356
Scrub now.

227
00:17:47,484 --> 00:17:49,614
Do you know when
my mama will come?

228
00:17:50,236 --> 00:17:51,236
Hush him up!

229
00:17:51,279 --> 00:17:52,279
Mama! Mama!

230
00:17:52,405 --> 00:17:53,405
Quiet.

231
00:17:53,615 --> 00:17:55,075
-Quiet, please.
-Mama!

232
00:17:55,241 --> 00:17:56,371
Hush him up!

233
00:17:56,493 --> 00:18:00,003
Your mother will come,
I swear she will. But you must be silent.

234
00:18:00,455 --> 00:18:02,075
Be silent.

235
00:18:09,089 --> 00:18:10,469
We need
a sympathetic ear.

236
00:18:10,548 --> 00:18:11,548
(RANDALL HUMMING)

237
00:18:11,591 --> 00:18:13,391
An opportunity to
explain our situation.

238
00:18:13,551 --> 00:18:15,551
Who, in your estimation,
is that sympathetic ear?

239
00:18:15,679 --> 00:18:17,469
The two men
I journeyed with.

240
00:18:17,597 --> 00:18:19,467
I'm certain they're making
enquiries at this very moment.

241
00:18:19,599 --> 00:18:21,059
I'd be just as
certain they're counting

242
00:18:21,226 --> 00:18:22,476
the money paid for
delivering you to this place.

243
00:18:22,602 --> 00:18:25,612
They were not kidnappers,
they were artists. Fellow performers.

244
00:18:25,980 --> 00:18:27,320
You know that?

245
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:29,440
You know for certain
who they were?

246
00:18:31,236 --> 00:18:35,316
The reality to come
is us being transported southward.

247
00:18:35,448 --> 00:18:37,528
New Orleans,
if I was to venture.

248
00:18:38,368 --> 00:18:40,618
After we arrive,
we'll be put to market.

249
00:18:40,995 --> 00:18:42,455
And beyond that...

250
00:18:43,415 --> 00:18:45,705
Well, I suppose once in a slave
state, there's only one outcome.

251
00:18:46,042 --> 00:18:46,542
No.

252
00:18:46,710 --> 00:18:48,550
I don't say that
to give you empty agitation, John.

253
00:18:48,712 --> 00:18:50,512
For y'all,
there ain't nothing but that.

254
00:18:50,630 --> 00:18:52,220
But John wasn't
kidnapped.

255
00:18:52,382 --> 00:18:54,682
John's just
being held as debt, that's all.

256
00:18:55,010 --> 00:18:56,970
Master pay his debt
and John be redeemed.

257
00:18:57,053 --> 00:18:58,433
Boy, our masters
will not come for us.

258
00:18:58,555 --> 00:19:00,595
John is sorry for y'all,
but that's how it be.

259
00:19:00,724 --> 00:19:02,644
Where you're going,
you're going without John.

260
00:19:04,686 --> 00:19:06,146
-RANDALL: Mama!
-Randall!

261
00:19:07,564 --> 00:19:08,734
Mama!

262
00:19:10,567 --> 00:19:12,397
Are you all right?

263
00:19:13,069 --> 00:19:14,399
Are you all right?

264
00:19:16,281 --> 00:19:17,281
Thank you, God.

265
00:19:19,492 --> 00:19:20,412
(DOOR OPENS)

266
00:19:20,493 --> 00:19:21,413
Come on. Get up.

267
00:19:21,661 --> 00:19:23,291
-I said, get up!
-ELIZA: No, don't--

268
00:19:23,413 --> 00:19:25,373
I don't want to
hear you talk! Get in the yard.

269
00:19:25,498 --> 00:19:26,458
Not my children!

270
00:19:26,583 --> 00:19:30,053
Ain't no need for all that.
Just taking a little trip, that's all.

271
00:19:30,587 --> 00:19:32,297
Don't want to
frighten the children

272
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:34,050
over a little
boat ride, do you?

273
00:19:34,215 --> 00:19:35,965
John's master
gonna pay his debt.

274
00:19:36,051 --> 00:19:37,051
Line up!

275
00:19:37,218 --> 00:19:38,218
His master gonna
pay his debt!

276
00:19:38,386 --> 00:19:40,056
(JOHN GROANING)

277
00:19:44,225 --> 00:19:46,975
I don't want to hear a word
out of none of you!

278
00:19:47,979 --> 00:19:49,229
Not a one.

279
00:20:02,369 --> 00:20:03,749
BURCH: All right, come on.

280
00:20:05,372 --> 00:20:07,252
-Move.
-Come on.

281
00:20:08,708 --> 00:20:10,288
Come on, child.
Come on.

282
00:20:10,418 --> 00:20:12,048
Follow your mama.

283
00:20:12,170 --> 00:20:13,170
Come on, boy.

284
00:20:13,213 --> 00:20:14,213
RADBURN: Up these stairs.

285
00:20:14,297 --> 00:20:16,507
BURCH: Get down out
of that wagon. Come on.

286
00:20:17,217 --> 00:20:18,507
Come on. Move it!

287
00:20:19,094 --> 00:20:20,394
Let's go!

288
00:20:20,470 --> 00:20:21,970
Up, up, up the stairs.

289
00:20:23,181 --> 00:20:24,601
Come on, let's go.

290
00:20:29,229 --> 00:20:30,609
Come on, move it!

291
00:20:31,064 --> 00:20:32,574
All right, come on.

292
00:20:34,442 --> 00:20:36,572
RADBURN: Hey, you. Get up.

293
00:20:37,070 --> 00:20:38,610
Sit down, right there.

294
00:20:39,072 --> 00:20:40,412
(BURCH LAUGHING)

295
00:20:41,241 --> 00:20:42,081
Come on.

296
00:20:43,743 --> 00:20:45,453
Right there. Just sit down.

297
00:21:21,740 --> 00:21:24,080
Cheer up and don't be so cast down.

298
00:21:29,414 --> 00:21:30,624
(DOOR SLAMS)

299
00:21:34,044 --> 00:21:38,344
If you want to survive,
do and say as little as possible.

300
00:21:39,591 --> 00:21:44,051
Tell no one who you really are
and tell no one you can read and write.

301
00:21:46,181 --> 00:21:49,141
Unless you want to be a dead nigger.

302
00:21:49,225 --> 00:21:50,515
(DOOR OPENS)

303
00:22:04,616 --> 00:22:06,276
MAN: Now keep your mouth shut.

304
00:22:14,042 --> 00:22:15,962
I say we fight.

305
00:22:16,961 --> 00:22:18,381
The crew is fairly small.

306
00:22:19,214 --> 00:22:21,384
Were it well planned,
I believe they could be strong-armed.

307
00:22:21,508 --> 00:22:23,388
Three can't go against the whole crew.

308
00:22:24,511 --> 00:22:26,511
The rest here are niggers.

309
00:22:26,971 --> 00:22:28,261
Born and bred slaves.

310
00:22:28,390 --> 00:22:30,600
Niggers ain't got no stomach for a fight.

311
00:22:30,725 --> 00:22:32,225
Not a damn one.

312
00:22:32,394 --> 00:22:36,194
All's I know,
if we get where we're traveling...

313
00:22:36,523 --> 00:22:38,073
we'll wish we'd died trying.

314
00:22:38,191 --> 00:22:40,571
Survival's not about certain death,

315
00:22:40,652 --> 00:22:43,242
it's about keeping your head down.

316
00:22:46,241 --> 00:22:49,081
Days ago, I was with my family...

317
00:22:50,537 --> 00:22:52,367
in my home.

318
00:22:53,998 --> 00:22:56,208
Now you tell me all is lost.

319
00:22:58,378 --> 00:23:01,548
"Tell no one who I am."
That's the way to survive?

320
00:23:04,968 --> 00:23:06,968
Well, I don't want to survive.

321
00:23:08,430 --> 00:23:11,520
I want to live.

322
00:24:10,492 --> 00:24:11,742
(LAUGHS)

323
00:24:13,536 --> 00:24:14,746
(STABS)

324
00:24:21,294 --> 00:24:22,384
(SCREAMING)

325
00:24:40,313 --> 00:24:42,073
Better off.

326
00:24:43,024 --> 00:24:44,484
Better than us.

327
00:25:01,459 --> 00:25:02,709
I don't see him.

328
00:25:03,044 --> 00:25:03,594
Clemens!

329
00:25:04,170 --> 00:25:05,590
-Clemens Ray!
-Master.

330
00:25:05,714 --> 00:25:07,094
-Clemens!
-Master Ray, sir!

331
00:25:07,215 --> 00:25:08,425
Master Ray!

332
00:25:08,550 --> 00:25:09,590
JONUS: Who's in charge here?

333
00:25:09,968 --> 00:25:10,968
I'm the captain!

334
00:25:11,052 --> 00:25:12,222
I'm Mr. Jonus Ray.

335
00:25:12,387 --> 00:25:14,057
My solicitor has
documentation...

336
00:25:14,180 --> 00:25:16,980
verifying the negro
known as Clemens Ray is my property.

337
00:25:17,058 --> 00:25:19,388
I know nothing of
this arrangement.

338
00:25:19,519 --> 00:25:21,309
JONUS: You are ordered to
return that property

339
00:25:21,396 --> 00:25:23,226
immediately or be
charged with thievery.

340
00:25:24,399 --> 00:25:25,569
Free him!

341
00:25:28,528 --> 00:25:29,608
Master.

342
00:25:29,738 --> 00:25:31,568
Master Ray, sir.

343
00:25:33,116 --> 00:25:34,076
Clemens!

344
00:25:34,242 --> 00:25:35,372
-Clemens!
-CAPTAIN: Get him back!

345
00:25:35,493 --> 00:25:37,003
Clemens!

346
00:25:37,495 --> 00:25:38,535
Clemens!

347
00:25:39,456 --> 00:25:40,326
Clemens!

348
00:26:10,403 --> 00:26:12,283
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

349
00:26:45,063 --> 00:26:46,273
(SINGING)

350
00:26:46,564 --> 00:26:48,024
Mr. Parker.

351
00:26:48,066 --> 00:26:51,356
Ah, Mr. Northup. Mrs. Northup.

352
00:26:51,528 --> 00:26:53,568
Solomon, could I interest you
in a new cravat?

353
00:26:53,697 --> 00:26:55,027
Pure silk, by way of the French.

354
00:26:55,156 --> 00:26:57,696
We're in need of
a fresh carryall for my Mrs.'s travels.

355
00:26:58,034 --> 00:26:58,704
Nothing more.

356
00:26:59,035 --> 00:27:00,575
The year has passed already.

357
00:27:00,704 --> 00:27:02,084
Off to work at Sandy Hill again?

358
00:27:02,247 --> 00:27:03,077
I am.

359
00:27:03,248 --> 00:27:04,498
I have just the thing.

360
00:27:04,624 --> 00:27:06,384
Something to suit your style...

361
00:27:06,459 --> 00:27:09,049
and yet sturdy enough
for the 40-mile round trip.

362
00:27:09,170 --> 00:27:10,170
It's beautiful.

363
00:27:10,296 --> 00:27:11,206
At what price?

364
00:27:11,381 --> 00:27:12,301
We will take it.

365
00:27:12,424 --> 00:27:15,554
Children, come see what you
father has just purchased for me.

366
00:27:15,677 --> 00:27:17,257
MR. PARKER: One moment, sir,
and you'll be assisted.

367
00:27:17,387 --> 00:27:19,177
-Mr. Parker.
-Sir?

368
00:27:19,305 --> 00:27:20,465
If we could discuss the price.

369
00:27:20,598 --> 00:27:22,308
Oh, forgive me, Solomon.
Forgive me, Mrs. Northup.

370
00:27:22,434 --> 00:27:24,484
A customer waits. Welcome, sir.

371
00:27:24,602 --> 00:27:26,482
SOLOMON: Shop well, sir,
but mind your wallet.

372
00:27:26,604 --> 00:27:28,404
MR. PARKER: Pay no attention
to this gentleman's nonsense.

373
00:27:28,565 --> 00:27:29,605
Jasper!

374
00:27:31,234 --> 00:27:33,074
My regrets for the intrusion, sir.

375
00:27:33,361 --> 00:27:35,071
SOLOMON: No intrusion.

376
00:27:38,742 --> 00:27:40,332
Good day, sir.

377
00:27:40,744 --> 00:27:42,084
MR. PARKER: Good day.

378
00:27:42,203 --> 00:27:43,753
Jasper, out.

379
00:27:52,047 --> 00:27:54,257
Very good. Very good.

380
00:27:54,549 --> 00:27:57,219
Let's see, here. Eliza!

381
00:27:58,470 --> 00:28:00,720
Stand up when you
hear your name. Eliza.

382
00:28:01,681 --> 00:28:02,561
Lethe!

383
00:28:06,061 --> 00:28:06,601
John.

384
00:28:08,396 --> 00:28:09,606
Oren.

385
00:28:11,024 --> 00:28:12,154
Platt.

386
00:28:15,070 --> 00:28:16,110
Platt.

387
00:28:19,240 --> 00:28:20,620
(SIGHS) Stand up.

388
00:28:22,619 --> 00:28:24,119
You fit the description given.

389
00:28:24,245 --> 00:28:25,535
Why didn't you answer when called?

390
00:28:25,663 --> 00:28:27,083
My name is not Platt.

391
00:28:27,248 --> 00:28:28,038
My name--

392
00:28:30,335 --> 00:28:32,045
Your name is Platt.

393
00:28:34,255 --> 00:28:36,375
Captain, get these niggers to my cart.

394
00:28:36,966 --> 00:28:38,716
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

395
00:28:49,145 --> 00:28:50,225
Mmm.

396
00:28:56,027 --> 00:28:57,107
(CHUCKLES)

397
00:28:58,488 --> 00:28:59,698
Move.

398
00:29:03,451 --> 00:29:05,121
FREEMAN: I believe I have
something very much

399
00:29:05,245 --> 00:29:06,705
to your liking in the back room.

400
00:29:07,038 --> 00:29:08,618
Follow me, please.

401
00:29:08,748 --> 00:29:11,578
Yes. Now, inspect them at your leisure...

402
00:29:11,710 --> 00:29:16,550
but I ask you to
pay particular regard to young Ezra here.

403
00:29:16,715 --> 00:29:18,085
Incredibly sound limbs.

404
00:29:18,216 --> 00:29:20,296
I have never seen anything
quite like him.

405
00:29:20,427 --> 00:29:23,347
And this marvelous creature.
Can you believe it? Mmm?

406
00:29:23,471 --> 00:29:25,181
She'll make a fine lady's maid.

407
00:29:25,306 --> 00:29:26,426
Madam? (CHUCKLES)

408
00:29:26,725 --> 00:29:28,475
So, inspect at your leisure.

409
00:29:28,601 --> 00:29:31,021
Take your time.
Help yourself to refreshments.

410
00:29:31,146 --> 00:29:34,146
Gentlemen, what catches
your fancy here? Hmm?

411
00:29:34,566 --> 00:29:35,566
This boy? Yes?

412
00:29:35,692 --> 00:29:38,032
Open your mouth. Open wider.

413
00:29:38,153 --> 00:29:40,493
Look in there.
Never been sick a day in his life.

414
00:29:40,613 --> 00:29:42,243
And I call particular attention to Martha.

415
00:29:42,365 --> 00:29:44,695
She is an excellent pastry cook.

416
00:29:45,035 --> 00:29:46,615
Ah, Mr. Ford.

417
00:29:47,162 --> 00:29:49,412
Splendid seeing you, sir.
What catches your fancy?

418
00:29:49,539 --> 00:29:51,539
This lad? He's very brawny.

419
00:29:51,666 --> 00:29:54,456
How much for the ones Platt and Eliza?

420
00:29:54,544 --> 00:29:56,214
Ah, yes.

421
00:29:56,504 --> 00:29:58,634
A thousand for Platt. Uh... Oh.

422
00:29:58,715 --> 00:30:01,545
This is a nigger of
considerable talent, I assure you.

423
00:30:01,676 --> 00:30:03,426
700 for Eliza.

424
00:30:03,553 --> 00:30:05,353
My fairest price.

425
00:30:05,597 --> 00:30:06,717
Mmm.

426
00:30:07,557 --> 00:30:08,727
You will accept a note?

427
00:30:09,059 --> 00:30:11,519
Please, sir. Do not divide my family.

428
00:30:11,644 --> 00:30:13,064
Do not take me unless you take my children.

429
00:30:13,229 --> 00:30:14,229
Eliza! Quiet!

430
00:30:14,356 --> 00:30:16,066
You will have the most faithful slave in me.

431
00:30:16,232 --> 00:30:17,482
The most faithful slave that has ever lived.

432
00:30:17,609 --> 00:30:18,739
But I beg that you do not separate us.

433
00:30:19,027 --> 00:30:20,067
Your price for the boy?

434
00:30:20,236 --> 00:30:21,446
Eliza! Stop it!

435
00:30:21,571 --> 00:30:22,741
I will give you something to cry about.

436
00:30:23,073 --> 00:30:25,243
Randall, come forward. Come, come, come.

437
00:30:25,367 --> 00:30:27,487
Now, do you see how fit this boy is?

438
00:30:27,619 --> 00:30:29,039
Like ripe fruit.

439
00:30:29,162 --> 00:30:32,082
May I take your stick a moment?
Observe this.

440
00:30:32,207 --> 00:30:34,167
Randall, jump, jump, jump. Run, run, run.

441
00:30:34,292 --> 00:30:36,462
Very good! Higher.

442
00:30:36,586 --> 00:30:37,666
Now, you see this.

443
00:30:38,004 --> 00:30:41,474
It's very likely
he will grow into a fine beast.

444
00:30:42,676 --> 00:30:44,426
600 for the boy.

445
00:30:44,552 --> 00:30:46,222
Fair and final.

446
00:30:46,680 --> 00:30:48,060
Done.

447
00:30:48,181 --> 00:30:50,481
Superb. A moment, please.

448
00:30:50,600 --> 00:30:52,020
Mr. Ford.

449
00:30:52,227 --> 00:30:53,307
-Please.
-Eliza!

450
00:30:53,478 --> 00:30:55,228
How much for the little girl?

451
00:30:55,313 --> 00:30:56,403
Ah...

452
00:30:56,731 --> 00:30:58,071
You have no use for her.

453
00:30:58,191 --> 00:30:59,731
One so young will bring you no profit.

454
00:31:00,068 --> 00:31:01,988
No, no, no. I cannot sell the girl.

455
00:31:02,112 --> 00:31:05,622
No, there's heaps
and piles of money to be made from her.

456
00:31:05,740 --> 00:31:08,200
She's a beauty. One of the regular bloods.

457
00:31:08,326 --> 00:31:11,116
None of your thick-lipped,
bullet-heated, cotton-picking niggers, here.

458
00:31:11,246 --> 00:31:13,996
Her child, man.

459
00:31:14,332 --> 00:31:15,082
Please.

460
00:31:15,208 --> 00:31:17,168
For God's sake,
are you not sentimental in the least?

461
00:31:17,293 --> 00:31:20,053
My sentimentality extends
the length of a coin.

462
00:31:20,213 --> 00:31:21,593
God, please.

463
00:31:22,257 --> 00:31:25,547
Now do you take this lot, Mr. Ford,
or do you pass on them?

464
00:31:25,719 --> 00:31:29,389
Please, please. Please.

465
00:31:29,472 --> 00:31:31,142
I will take the ones Platt and Eliza.

466
00:31:31,266 --> 00:31:32,266
Sold, Eliza and Platt.

467
00:31:32,392 --> 00:31:33,482
I will not go without my children!

468
00:31:33,601 --> 00:31:34,691
Goddamn sniveling wench!

469
00:31:35,020 --> 00:31:36,060
You will not take them from me!

470
00:31:36,229 --> 00:31:37,479
God damn you! Get her out of here, Cape!

471
00:31:37,564 --> 00:31:39,024
(CHILDREN SCREAMING)

472
00:31:39,149 --> 00:31:40,729
Please! No! No!

473
00:31:41,067 --> 00:31:42,567
Get her out of here, god damn it!

474
00:31:42,694 --> 00:31:45,664
Platt, get your fiddle.
Play, play, play something.

475
00:31:45,989 --> 00:31:49,079
I will give you something to cry
about, you goddamned witch!

476
00:31:49,200 --> 00:31:51,330
Get her out of here, Cape! Out, now!

477
00:31:51,536 --> 00:31:53,246
(PLAYING LIVELY TUNE)

478
00:31:53,329 --> 00:31:55,039
CHILDREN: Mama! Mama! Mama!

479
00:31:55,749 --> 00:31:57,709
Yes.

480
00:31:58,043 --> 00:32:00,633
Mr. Ford, a pleasure.

481
00:32:01,046 --> 00:32:02,586
(CHILDREN CONTINUE SCREAMING)

482
00:32:17,354 --> 00:32:19,564
Did you bring all those niggers?

483
00:32:19,689 --> 00:32:22,069
Two of them? You got two?

484
00:32:22,400 --> 00:32:23,070
FORD: Mr. Chapin.

485
00:32:23,193 --> 00:32:23,653
(SOBBING)

486
00:32:24,402 --> 00:32:26,742
MISTRESS FORD: This one's crying.
Why is this one crying?

487
00:32:27,072 --> 00:32:28,572
FORD: Separated from her children.

488
00:32:28,698 --> 00:32:30,238
-Oh, dear.
-It couldn't be helped.

489
00:32:30,408 --> 00:32:31,578
Poor, poor woman.

490
00:32:31,701 --> 00:32:33,081
-Mr. Chapin.
-Yes, sir.

491
00:32:33,244 --> 00:32:34,624
Tomorrow, you have to take these two

492
00:32:34,746 --> 00:32:36,286
up to the mill and start them working.

493
00:32:36,414 --> 00:32:37,624
For now, make them adequate.

494
00:32:37,749 --> 00:32:39,539
Fix them a meal
and have them rest themselves.

495
00:32:39,668 --> 00:32:41,038
Yes, sir.

496
00:32:41,961 --> 00:32:43,091
Come on, now.

497
00:32:43,546 --> 00:32:45,716
Come on! Don't dawdle!

498
00:32:46,091 --> 00:32:48,591
Something to eat, and some rest.

499
00:32:48,968 --> 00:32:50,218
Your children will soon be forgotten.

500
00:33:17,747 --> 00:33:19,997
For all of you raw niggers
that don't know...

501
00:33:20,125 --> 00:33:24,415
my name is John Tibeats,
William Ford's chief carpenter.

502
00:33:24,546 --> 00:33:28,046
You will refer to me as "Master."

503
00:33:28,216 --> 00:33:31,966
Mr. Chapin is the overseer
on this plantation.

504
00:33:32,095 --> 00:33:36,555
You, too, will refer to him as "Master."

505
00:33:37,642 --> 00:33:39,562
So, clap your hands.

506
00:33:43,231 --> 00:33:45,981
Like this. Come on.

507
00:33:46,651 --> 00:33:49,071
Come on, now. Clap your hands.

508
00:33:53,158 --> 00:33:55,408
(SINGING) <i>Nigger run
Nigger flew</i>

509
00:33:55,577 --> 00:33:58,077
<i>Nigger tore his shirt in two</i>

510
00:33:58,204 --> 00:34:00,464
<i>Run, run
The pattyroller will get you</i>

511
00:34:00,582 --> 00:34:02,672
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away</i>

512
00:34:07,297 --> 00:34:09,217
TIBEATS: <i>That's right.
Like you mean it.</i>

513
00:34:10,216 --> 00:34:12,386
(SINGING) <i>Nigger run
Run so fast</i>

514
00:34:12,469 --> 00:34:14,969
<i>Stove his head in a hornet's nest</i>

515
00:34:15,055 --> 00:34:17,055
<i>Run, run
The pattyroller will get you</i>

516
00:34:17,223 --> 00:34:20,233
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away</i>

517
00:34:21,019 --> 00:34:23,229
<i>Run, nigger, run
The pattyroller will get you</i>

518
00:34:23,396 --> 00:34:25,516
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away</i>

519
00:34:27,525 --> 00:34:29,565
<i>Some folk say a nigger don't steal</i>

520
00:34:29,694 --> 00:34:32,034
<i>I caught three in my corn field</i>

521
00:34:32,155 --> 00:34:34,275
<i>One has a bushel
And one has a peck</i>

522
00:34:34,407 --> 00:34:36,577
<i>One has a rope
It was hung around his neck</i>

523
00:34:36,701 --> 00:34:39,251
<i>Run, nigger, run
The pattyroller will get you</i>

524
00:34:39,371 --> 00:34:41,541
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away</i>

525
00:34:41,664 --> 00:34:43,964
<i>Run, nigger, run
The pattyroller will get you</i>

526
00:34:44,084 --> 00:34:46,674
<i>Run, nigger, run
Well, you better get away</i>

527
00:34:47,003 --> 00:34:49,263
<i>Hey, Mr. Pattyroller
Don't catch me</i>

